<span id="v.v.xxvi-p1"></span> <span class="c1"><span
id="v.v.xxvi-p1.1"></span>Chapter XXVI.—The Method Observed in the
History of the Creation, in Reply to the Perverse Interpretation of
Hermogenes.</span>

<span id="v.v.xxvi-p2"></span>We, however, have but one God, and but
<span id="page_492">p. 492</span> <span
id="v.v.xxvi-Page_492"></span>one earth too, which in the beginning God
made. <span id="fr_6365"></span>[6366](#fn_6365.md) The Scripture, which at
its very outset proposes to run through the order thereof tells us as
its first information that it was created; it next proceeds to set forth
what sort of earth it was. <span id="fr_6366"></span>[6367](#fn_6366.md) In
like manner with respect to the heaven, it informs us first of its
creation—“In the beginning God made the heaven:” <span
id="fr_6367"></span>[6368](#fn_6367.md) it then goes on to introduce its
arrangement; how that God both separated “the water which was below the
firmament from that which was above the firmament,” <span
id="fr_6368"></span>[6369](#fn_6368.md) and called the firmament
heaven, <span id="fr_6369"></span>[6370](#fn_6369.md) —the very thing He
had created in the beginning.  Similarly it (afterwards) treats of man: 
“And God created man, in the image of God made He him.” <span
id="fr_6370"></span>[6371](#fn_6370.md) It next reveals how He made him:
“And (the Lord) God formed man of the dust of the ground, and breathed
into his nostrils the breath of life; and man became a living
soul.” <span id="fr_6371"></span>[6372](#fn_6371.md) Now this is
undoubtedly <span id="fr_6372"></span>[6373](#fn_6372.md) the correct and
fitting mode for the narrative.  First comes a prefatory statement, then
follow the details in full; <span id="fr_6373"></span>[6374](#fn_6373.md)
first the subject is named, then it is described. <span
id="fr_6374"></span>[6375](#fn_6374.md) How absurd is the other view of the
account, <span id="fr_6375"></span>[6376](#fn_6375.md) when even before
he <span id="fr_6376"></span>[6377](#fn_6376.md) had premised any mention
of his subject, *i.e.* Matter, without even giving us its name, he all
on a sudden promulged its form and condition, describing to us its
quality before mentioning its existence,—pointing out the figure of the
thing formed, *but* concealing its name! But how much more credible is
our opinion, which holds that Scripture has only subjoined the
arrangement of the subject after it has first duly described its
formation and mentioned its name!  Indeed, how full and complete <span
id="fr_6377"></span>[6378](#fn_6377.md) is the meaning of these words: “In
the beginning God created the heaven and the earth; but <span
id="fr_6378"></span>[6379](#fn_6378.md) the earth was without form, and
void,” <span id="fr_6379"></span>[6380](#fn_6379.md) —the very same earth,
no doubt, which God made, and of which the Scripture had been speaking
at that very moment. <span id="fr_6380"></span>[6381](#fn_6380.md) For that
very “*but*” <span id="fr_6381"></span>[6382](#fn_6381.md) is inserted into
the narrative like a clasp, <span id="fr_6382"></span>[6383](#fn_6382.md)
(in its function) of a conjunctive particle, to connect *the two
sentences indissolubly together*: “*But* the earth.” This word carries
back the mind to that earth of which mention had just been made, and
binds the sense thereunto. <span id="fr_6383"></span>[6384](#fn_6383.md)
Take away this “but,” and the tie is loosened; so much so that the
passage, “But the earth was without form, and void,” may then seem to
have been meant for any other earth.

